[[File:Status set.png|thumb|An example of a status set]]
A '''status set''' is a collection of [[social status]]es that an individual holds. A person may have status of a daughter, wife, mother, student, worker, church member and a citizen.

The term "status set" was coined by [[Robert K. Merton]] in 1957. He made a clear distinction between a "[[role set]]" and a "status set".<ref>Robert K. Merton "On social structure and science" {{ISBN|0-226-52071-4}}, page 113</ref>

Merton stated that status set is the set of statuses in a society while role set is the set of roles in a society


